(41, 4, 41, 32, 1, 9, 10, 'feared exceedingly', 'Fear of the Lord', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of fear in response to divine power. In Mark, the disciples fear Jesus'' authority over nature, while in Jonah, the sailors fear the Lord after learning about Jonah''s disobedience.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 41, 32, 1, 15, 16, 'feared exceedingly', 'Fear and Authority Over Nature', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of fear in response to divine authority over nature. In Mark, the disciples fear Jesus after he calms the storm, while in Jonah, the sailors fear the Lord after the sea ceases its raging. This connection highlights the recognition of divine power.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 1, 42, 8, 26, 39, 'the country of the Gadarenes', 'Jesus in the Gadarenes', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' arrival in the country of the Gadarenes, where he encounters a man possessed by demons. This connection highlights the miraculous healing that occurs as a result of this encounter.', 'parallel', 0.43999999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 1, 40, 8, 28, 34, 'the other side of the sea', 'Geographical Connection of Jesus'' Journey', 'Both passages describe Jesus arriving at the other side of the sea, indicating a geographical link. This connection highlights the transition into a new region where significant events occur.', 'parallel', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 1, 41, 4, 35, 35, 'other side', 'Journey to the Other Side', 'Both passages emphasize the journey across the sea. Mark 4:35 introduces the intention to ''pass over unto the other side,'' which is fulfilled in Mark 5:1 when they arrive in the country of the Gadarenes.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 2, 41, 1, 23, 23, 'a man with an unclean spirit', 'Connection of Unclean Spirits', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of a man with an unclean spirit, highlighting the theme of spiritual affliction. This connection illustrates the pervasive nature of unclean spirits in different settings, from the synagogue to the tombs.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 2, 23, 65, 4, 4, 'unclean spirit', 'Connection of Unclean Spirits', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of individuals associated with graves and unclean practices. The man in Mark is described as having an unclean spirit, while Isaiah mentions those who remain among the graves and consume abominable things.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 2, 41, 5, 8, 8, 'unclean spirit', 'Connection of Unclean Spirit', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of an unclean spirit in the man. The first verse introduces the man with the unclean spirit, while the second verse records Jesus commanding that spirit to come out.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 2, 42, 9, 42, 42, 'unclean spirit', 'Connection of Unclean Spirits', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of unclean spirits and Jesus'' authority to rebuke and heal those afflicted. The man in Mark is confronted by an unclean spirit, while in Luke, Jesus rebukes an unclean spirit affecting a child.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 2, 42, 8, 27, 27, 'out of the tombs', 'Connection of Demoniac Encounters', 'Both passages emphasize a man with unclean spirits who dwells among tombs. This highlights the shared theme of demonic possession and isolation in similar settings.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 3, 23, 65, 4, 4, 'among the tombs', 'Connection of Tombs and Graves', 'Both passages emphasize dwelling among the dead, highlighting a shared theme of isolation and spiritual desolation. The mention of ''tombs'' in Mark and ''graves'' in Isaiah suggests a parallel in the depiction of those living in deathly environments.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 3, 42, 8, 29, 29, 'no man could bind him, no, not with chains', 'Connection of Demonic Affliction', 'Both passages emphasize the man''s inability to be restrained due to the influence of an unclean spirit. They describe his experience of being bound with chains and the supernatural strength that allows him to break free.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 3, 27, 4, 32, 33, NULL, 'Isolation and Wildness in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the theme of isolation from society and living among wild elements. Both passages depict individuals who are driven away from human companionship, with one dwelling among tombs and the other with beasts.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 3, 41, 9, 18, 22, NULL, 'Connection of Demonic Affliction', 'Both passages emphasize the torment caused by unclean spirits. In Mark 5:3, the man among the tombs is uncontrollable, while in Mark 9:18-22, the boy is similarly afflicted, exhibiting violent behavior. This connection highlights the destructive nature of demonic possession.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 4, 59, 3, 7, 8, 'neither could any man tame him', 'Connection of Taming and Control', 'This connection highlights the struggle of taming both the man in Mark and the tongue in James. Both passages emphasize the difficulty of controlling powerful forces, whether they be physical strength or verbal expression.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 5, 11, 18, 28, 28, 'crying, and cutting himself with stones', 'Self-harm and Crying Out', 'Both passages emphasize the act of crying and cutting oneself, highlighting a theme of desperation and anguish. The physical act of self-harm connects the emotional turmoil experienced by the individuals in each context.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 5, 18, 2, 7, 8, 'cutting himself with stones', 'Connection of Suffering and Self-Harm', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of intense suffering and self-inflicted harm. In Mark, the man is ''crying, and cutting himself with stones,'' while Job uses a ''potsherd to scrape himself.''', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 5, 43, 8, 44, 44, 'crying, and cutting himself', 'Connection of Despair and Evil', 'This connection highlights the theme of suffering and the influence of evil. In Mark, the man is tormented, crying and cutting himself, while in John, the devil is described as a liar and a murderer, suggesting a link between despair and malevolent forces.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 6, 59, 2, 19, 19, 'worshipped him', 'Belief and Worship Connection', 'This connection highlights the act of worship in Mark 5:6, where the man recognizes Jesus and runs to him. Similarly, James 2:19 notes that even demons believe in God and tremble, indicating that belief alone does not equate to true worship or faith.', 'theme', 0.363, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 6, 19, 66, 3, 3, 'worshipped him', 'Worship and Submission to God', 'This connection highlights the theme of reverence towards God. In Mark 5:6, the act of worship signifies recognition of Jesus'' authority, while Psalms 66:3 emphasizes that enemies will submit to God''s power.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 6, 42, 4, 41, 41, NULL, 'Recognition of Jesus'' Authority', 'This connection highlights the recognition of Jesus'' identity by both the possessed man in Mark and the demons in Luke. Both passages emphasize the acknowledgment of Jesus as the Son of God, showcasing His authority over evil spirits.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 6, 19, 72, 9, 9, 'worshipped him', 'Worship and Bowing Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of bowing or worshipping before a figure of authority. In Mark 5:6, the act of worship is directed towards Jesus, while Psalms 72:9 speaks of those who bow before him, suggesting a thematic link between reverence and submission.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 6, 44, 16, 17, 17, 'worshipped him', 'Recognition of Divine Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of recognition of divine authority. In both passages, individuals respond to Jesus and Paul with reverence, acknowledging their roles as servants of God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 7, 40, 8, 29, 29, NULL, 'Connection Between Demonic Encounters', 'Both passages emphasize the demons'' recognition of Jesus as the ''Son of God'' and their fear of being tormented. This connection highlights a shared theme of spiritual authority and the demons'' plea for mercy.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 7, 44, 16, 17, 17, 'most high God', 'Connection of ''Most High God''', 'Both passages emphasize the title ''Most High God'', linking the recognition of divine authority. In Mark, the demon acknowledges Jesus as ''Son of the most high God'', while in Acts, the spirit proclaims Paul and his companions as ''servants of the most high God''.', 'keyword', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 7, 40, 26, 63, 63, 'I adjure thee by God', 'Invocation of God''s Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the act of adjuring by God, highlighting the authority and recognition of Jesus as the Son of God. The demoniac in Mark acknowledges Jesus'' divine status, while the high priest in Matthew demands a confession of that same identity.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 7, 65, 1, 6, 6, 'thou Son of the most high God', 'Connection of Authority and Judgment', 'This connection highlights the authority of Jesus as the Son of the Most High God in Mark, which parallels the judgment of rebellious angels in Jude. Both passages emphasize the theme of divine authority over spiritual beings and their ultimate fate.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 7, 41, 3, 11, 11, 'thou Son of the most high God', 'Recognition of Jesus'' Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the recognition of Jesus as the Son of God by unclean spirits. In Mark 5:7, the spirit acknowledges Jesus'' divine authority, while in Mark 3:11, they fall down and proclaim him as the Son of God.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 7, 42, 8, 28, 28, 'thou Son of the most high God', 'Connection of Demonic Recognition', 'Both passages emphasize the recognition of Jesus as ''Son of the most high God'' and express a plea to not be tormented. This parallel highlights the fear and acknowledgment of Jesus'' authority by the demonic presence.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 7, 44, 19, 13, 13, 'I adjure thee by God', 'Invocation of Jesus'' Name', 'This connection highlights the invocation of Jesus'' name in both passages. In Mark 5:7, the evil spirit acknowledges Jesus as the Son of God, while in Acts 19:13, exorcists invoke Jesus'' name to command spirits, reflecting a shared theme of authority over evil.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
